Samuel wrote:
&gt; I&#39;m trying to do a job based on a recovery thru JMX but unsuccessfuly
&gt; so far. I&#39;ve created a script that takes the last Job from the jobs
&gt; folder and assembles both order.xml and seeds.txt in a job.jar file.
&gt; Before I change the order.xml&#39;s recover-path to that last job&#39;s
&gt; recover.gz path, like:
&gt;
&gt; &lt;string
&gt; name=&quot;recover-path&quot;&gt;/usr/heritrix-1.6.0/jobs/JOB_FOLDER/logs/recover.gz&lt;/string&gt;
&gt;
&gt; The job starts OK but its not based on a recovery like I usually would
&gt; do thru the web interface.
&gt;
&gt; Am I forgetting something??
No.

The way the submit-new-job works when you go via JMX is that upon 
submission, the job jar is unbundled and then a new job is created that 
is based on the unbundled jar.  A quick look at the code shows no reason 
why this type of recover should not work (Start here: 
http://crawler.archive.org/xref/org/archive/crawler/Heritrix.html#1165).

If you look at the order file in the UI, does it show &#39;recover-path&#39; 
pointing to the right place (or is it empty)?  Does the recover.gz 
pointed to for sure exist?  Anything in heritrix_out.log?

Any particular reason for your favoring the old style recover.gz log 
over checkpointing?
